    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-03-05T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-03-05T21:00:00-05:00" n="485"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d485">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Control (Korea)/3–146: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Political Adviser in Korea</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Benninghoff</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-03-05T21:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 5, 1946—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>32. <gloss target="#t_urtel1">Urtel</gloss> 33 undated reed Mar. 1.<note n="61"
                        xml:id="d485fn1">Not printed; it requested information on “possible American
                        commitments made to Russians at Yalta, Potsdam or Moscow” that “Russians
                        might bring up to defend their actions should the question of removal of
                        capital goods from Korea arise.” (740.00119 Control (Korea)/3–146)</note> No
                    commitment made to Russians by US Govt on disposition <gloss target="#t_Jap1"
                        >Jap</gloss> property in Korea. US views on handling of <gloss
                        target="#t_Jap1">Jap</gloss> property in liberated areas presented in note
                    by Am <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> Moscow to Foreign Commissariat
                    following <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> Aug 28, 1945.<note n="62"
                        xml:id="d485fn2">Telegram 1923 to Moscow, <ref target="frus1945v06#pg_990">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1945, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">vi</hi>, p. 990</ref>.</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> also cabled on Feb 28 to Am <gloss
                        target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> Moscow<note n="63" xml:id="d485fn3">Telegram
                        349 to Moscow; see telegram 1868 to London, <ref target="#pg_480">p.
                            480</ref>.</note> US views on reparations policy with inst to explore
                    informally with Soviet Govt. Relevant portions of reference tels contents of
                    which have not been made public are quoted below for your <gloss
                        target="#t_Info1">info</gloss>. No replies received from Soviets.</p>
                <p>[Here follow quotations from two telegrams cited.]</p>
                <p>Sent to Seoul and repeated to Moscow [as] 394.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
